Here is the Java code that performs a binary search on a sorted array to find a specific element:

```java
public class BinarySearchExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 15};
        int target = 7;
        int index = binarySearch(arr, target);
        if (index == -1) {
            System.out.println("Element not found");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Element found at index: " + index);
        }
    }

    // Binary search algorithm
    public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
        int low = 0;
        int high = arr.length - 1;

        while (low <= high) {
            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
            if (arr[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
                low = mid + 1;
            } else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

This Java code includes a binary search function (`binarySearch`) that takes a sorted array and a target element as input, and returns the index of the target element if it is found, or -1 if it is not. The binary search algorithm is implemented by repeatedly dividing the search interval in half. If the target element is found, the index is returned. If the target element is not found, the algorithm returns -1. The main method tests the binary search function with the given sorted array and target element.

