How can I sort a list of integers in Java without using any built-in sorting functions or libraries? Here is an unsorted list of integers for you to work with:
int[] nums = {5, 2, 9, 1, 3, 8};
You can only use basic Java code and logical reasoning to come up with a solution. Can you figure out how to implement a sorting algorithm from scratch to sort this list in ascending order? Good luck!

response_A:
There are many ways to sort a list of integers in Java without using any built-in sorting functions or libraries. One popular and simple sorting algorithm is the Bubble Sort algorithm. Here's how you can implement it:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {5, 2, 9, 1, 3, 8};
        bubbleSort(nums);
    }

    public static void bubbleSort(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
                if (nums[j] > nums[j+1]) {
                    // Swap nums[j] and nums[j+1]
                    int temp = nums[j];
                    nums[j] = nums[j+1];
                    nums[j+1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This code will sort the `nums` array in ascending order using the Bubble Sort algorithm. However, it's important to note that Bubble Sort is not the most efficient sorting algorithm, especially for large lists of integers. For larger lists, you might want to consider more efficient algorithms like Quick Sort, Merge Sort, or Heap Sort. But for small lists like this, Bubble Sort is a simple and straightforward solution.

